ese variations affect the Earth's environment, from long-term paleoclimate effects to century timescales in the context of human-induced climate change, and from signals of the 11-year sunspot cycle to the impacts of solar emissions on space weather in our planet's upper atmosphere.Written by two of the leading authorities on the subject, The Sun's Influence on Climate is an essential primer for students and nonspecialists alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aClimatic changesxEffect of solar activity on. 0aSolar-terrestrial physics. 0aWeatherxEffect of solar activity on. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / General.2bisacsh  aEUV.  aEarth.  aSun.  aUV radiation.  aUV.  aX-ray wavelengths.  aatmosphere.  aatmospheric composition.  aaverage temperature.  abiological processes.  abiosphere.  achemical processes.  aclimate change.  aclimate system.  aclimate.  acoronal mass ejections.  acryosphere.  adendrochronology.  aenergy source.  aglobal wind patterns.  ahuman activity.  ainfrared.  alower stratosphere.  amagnetic field.  ameteorological balloons.  ameteorological records.  anatural factors.  apaleoclimate.  aphysical processes.  aproxy data.  aradiation budget.  aradiation.  aregression analysis.  asolar activity.  asolar atmosphere.  asolar corona.  asolar cycle.  asolar emissions.  asolar energy.  asolar heating.  asolar luminosity.  asolar magnetic field.  asolar radiation.  asolar wind.  aspace environment.  aspace weather.  asunspots.  asurface temperature.  atemperature.  atemporal variation.  aweather variations.1 aCargill, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066